    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Campanula biebersteiniana are iridoids, phenylethanoid glycosides, flavonoids, and saponins. The iridoids, specifically 6-hydroxyjaconine, are known for their anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties due to their ability to inhibit the production of pro-inflammatory cytokines and their interaction with cell membranes. The phenylethanoid glycosides, particularly adenosine and convalatoxin, exhibit vasodilatory and anti-inflammatory effects, contributing to their potential use in cardiovascular and neurological disorders. Flavonoids, including quercetin and kaempferol, have been shown to possess antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antiviral properties, which may contribute to their protective effects against oxidative stress and inflammation. Saponins, such as campanulin, have been found to possess anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial activities, likely due to their ability to disrupt cell membranes and inhibit the growth of microorganisms.",
